{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513839"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.31,0.13,0.15,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114502"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1501"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"3883"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8147"},{"type":"tags","id":"12095"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of progressive skin discolouration and swelling of her right breast. There has been warmth and tenderness but no discharge. She does not report any fevers, chills, nausea, or vomiting. A week ago, she was diagnosed with mastitis, for which she was prescribed a seven-day course of dicloxacillin. Despite adherence to the medical regimen, her symptoms have worsened. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has two children, menarche was at 13, menopause at 52. Her last mammogram was two years ago and did not show any suspicious lesions. On examination, she appears well. Her blood pressure is 124/78 mmHg, pulse 75/min, temperature 37\u00b0C, respiratory rate 12/min and SpO2 100% on room air. Gross examination of the breast is shown (Image). There are palpable lymph nodes in her right axilla that are firm and fixed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to diagnose the underlying condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI of the breast","Fine-needle aspiration of the axillary nodes","Ultrasound of breast and axilla","Mammogram","Skin punch biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture highly suggestive of inflammatory breast cancer. This is an aggressive subtype invasive breast cancer and is rare, accounting for less than 1% of all breast cancers. Understandably in this case it was initially diagnosed and treated as mastitis (erythema, warmth, tenderness, redness), but antibiotics and anti-inflammatory agents failed to resolve it because it was not mastitis. When mastitis fails to resolve with conservative therapy, this must raise suspicion for inflammatory breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe criteria for a diagnosis for inflammatory breast cancer include: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema of \u0026gt;1/3rd of the breast,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptom duration \u0026lt;6 months, and\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiopsy showing evidence of invasive carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnfortunately named, inflammatory breast cancer has no inflammatory cells but rather cancerous ductal cells that try to form ducts within the lymphatics. This compromises the drainage of the breast, resulting in oedema. The oedema causes the affected area to swell, and stagnant blood flow causes the colour changes. In advanced cases, tethering of the swollen breast at the hair follicles gives the classic \u0027peau d\u0027orange\u0027 appearance (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin punch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic test for inflammatory breast cancer. This is because the hallmark of inflammatory breast cancer is the presence of tumour emboli in the dermal lymphatics, which can be identified through a skin biopsy. The characteristic skin changes (erythema, oedema, peau d\u0027orange) are due to tumour cells blocking the lymphatic vessels in the skin, and a punch biopsy can directly sample these areas to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine-needle aspiration of the axillary nodes\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful for staging purposes if inflammatory breast cancer is confirmed, as it can determine whether the cancer has spread to the lymph nodes. However, it is not the most direct way to diagnose inflammatory breast cancer itself, which is primarily characterized by dermal lymphatic invasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of breast and axilla\u003C/strong\u003E can help identify masses and abnormal lymph nodes, but inflammatory breast cancer often presents without a discrete mass. While ultrasound is a valuable tool in the overall assessment, it is less specific for diagnosing inflammatory breast cancer compared to a skin biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammogram\u003C/strong\u003E is an important imaging modality for breast cancer detection, but it has limitations in diagnosing inflammatory breast cancer. The diffuse skin thickening and increased density seen on mammography in inflammatory breast cancer are non-specific findings that can also be seen in mastitis. Additionally, the absence of a discrete mass makes mammography less useful for diagnosis in this specific scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eof the breast \u003C/strong\u003Ecan provide detailed images and is more sensitive than mammography or ultrasound for detecting inflammatory breast cancer. It can show skin thickening, oedema, and enhancement patterns suggestive of inflammatory breast cancer. However, while MRI may help in assessing the extent of disease, it cannot provide the definitive histological diagnosis that a skin punch biopsy can offer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inflammatory breast cancer presents with skin changes, breast swelling, and warmth that can mimic mastitis but fails to respond to antibiotics.","Skin punch biopsy is the most appropriate diagnostic test for inflammatory breast cancer as it can identify malignant cells in dermal lymphatics.","Inflammatory breast cancer is an aggressive form of breast cancer characterized by cancer cells blocking lymphatic vessels rather than true inflammation."],"references":["Budny A, Staros\u0142awska E, Budny B, W\u00f3jcik R, Hys M, Koz\u0142owski P, Budny W, Brodzik A, Burdan F. Epidemiologia oraz diagnostyka raka piersi [Epidemiology and diagnosis of breast cancer]. Pol Merkur Lekarski. 2019 May 27;46(275):195-204. Polish. PMID: 31152530.","Rea D, Francis A, Hanby A, et al. Inflammatory breast cancer: time to standardise diagnosis assessment and management, and for the joining of forces to facilitate effective research. Br J Cancer. 2015. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/bjc2015115#Tab1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19964"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19965"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19964"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9c4bb140-6538-42a3-bf4f-81f66fc7d2ce.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9c4bb140-6538-42a3-bf4f-81f66fc7d2ce.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":392}},{"type":"media","id":"19965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19965"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0605fb3-b244-4917-a7d1-f19630a864c9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0605fb3-b244-4917-a7d1-f19630a864c9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T09:27:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T09:27:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114502"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":nu